Java Development Kit (JDK)¶

JDK represents a toolset for developing Java applications. Consists of Java compiler(javac), Java Virtual Machine(JVM), standard libraries, documentation and other tools.

JDK Structure¶

Javac¶

Java compiler compiles .java text files into .class files that contains byte code for further running on JVM. This files can be run on any machine on any platform that has the JVM installed.

Simplest Java Program¶

Java application, even the simplest one, contains the following lines of code:

In [1]:
public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello World");
    }
}

Every java file contains a class definition class ClassName {} Class is like a blueprint for some entity. If class declared as public - name of .java file should match the name of the this class. Java program should have an entry point of a program - main method. It should be public and static.
public - keywords used to define a member available for everyone outside the class definition.
static - keyword used to define a variable as a class variable. Classes maintain one copy of class variables regardless of how many instances exist of that class. "static" can also be used to define a method as a class method. Class methods are invoked by the class instead of a specific instance, and can only operate on class variables.
void keyword used to define a return type of a function. It means that function doesn't return anything.
String[] args - array of command line arguments of the type String.
System - java standard library's class name
out - static field, represents a standard output stream(in out case - the console).
println - static method, that user standard output stream and print messages.
